{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636841"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17610"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17610"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78222"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10324"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63631"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7319"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24167"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78222"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe erector spinae muscles form three distinct columns that run parallel to the vertebral column. These deep back muscles are essential for maintaining upright posture and controlling spinal movements.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the arrangement of the erector spinae muscles from lateral to medial?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spinalis, longissimus, iliocostalis","Iliocostalis, longissimus, spinalis","Longissimus, iliocostalis, spinalis","Spinalis, iliocostalis, longissimus","Longissimus, spinalis, iliocostalis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe erector spinae muscle group consists of three parallel columns that run alongside the vertebral column. From lateral (outside) to medial (inside) position, these columns are the \u003Cstrong\u003Eiliocostalis\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Elongissimus\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Espinalis\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect arrangements are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinalis, longissimus, iliocostalis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the reverse of the correct order\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELongissimus, iliocostalis, spinalis\u003C/strong\u003E - The iliocostalis is the most lateral muscle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinalis, iliocostalis, longissimus\u003C/strong\u003E - The spinalis is the most medial muscle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELongissimus, spinalis, iliocostalis\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement is incorrect as iliocostalis is lateral\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese muscles work together as powerful extensors of the vertebral column and are crucial for maintaining upright posture. Each column has distinct attachments and specific roles in spinal movement and stability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The erector spinae muscles comprise three parallel columns: iliocostalis (lateral), longissimus (intermediate), and spinalis (medial).","The erector spinae muscles are the primary extensors of the vertebral column.","Each column of erector spinae has distinct attachments and roles in maintaining posture and spinal stability."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cErector Spinae\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is under Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gray389.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63631"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17610"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21346"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21346"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D9VTUICexU5ymRpvEU3M5QmVmkOP3J.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D9VTUICexU5ymRpvEU3M5QmVmkOP3J.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":1207}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63631"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:41:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:43:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10324"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78222"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":nul